Optional: a trick to knit pdf

In this part, I will show you a small trick to turn your .Rmd file into a .pdf file directly.

Click on the dropdown arrow next to the “Knit” button, and select Knit to PDF.

If Rstudio gives some error, try pasting the following code in the console.

tinytex::install_tinytex()

Part I: Bike Path Usage

Data were collected on the volume of bicycle path users on the Northampton Rail Trail in Florence, Massachusetts. Variables in the dataset include the number of crossings on a particular day (volume, measured by a sensor near the intersection with Chestnut Street) and the average of the daily low and high temperatures for that day in degrees Fahrenheit (avgtemp), among other variables.

The data is preloaded for you and called railtrail

  1. Make a scatter plot with the volume variable on the vertical axis and the avgtemp variable on the horizontal axis.

  1. Describe the shape of the relationship between the volume and avgtemp variables. Also, discuss whether there are any outliers or gaps.

  2. Would it be appropriate to use the correlation between these variables to summarize the strength and direction of the relationship between these variables?

Part II: Arcade Revenue and Lawyers in Wyoming

Data were collected on the total revenue of arcades in the US (in millions of dollars) and the number of lawyers in Wyoming in each year from 2000 to 2009.

The data is preloaded for you, and is named arcade_lawyers.

  1. Make a scatter plot with total_arcade_revenue on the horizontal axis and lawyers_in_Wyoming on the vertical axis.

  1. Describe the direction, form, and strength of the relationship between arcade revenue and the number of lawyers in Wyoming

  2. Would it be appropriate to summarize the strength and direction of the relationship between these variables with the correlation coefficient?

  3. Calculate the correlation between these variables.

  1. Describe the strength and direction of the relationship between these variables, with reference to the scatter plot and the correlation coefficient (if appropriate).

  2. Do the correlation and relationship that you described above mean that there is a causal relationship between arcade revenue and the number of lawyers in Wyoming?
